%[text] # F04: Molecular Similarity
%[text] EasyMolKit Basic Tutorial — Layer 1
%[text] 
%[text] When we think, "I want to find new drug candidates that have effects similar to caffeine," how can we quantify the "degree of similarity" between molecules? Comparing them visually introduces subjectivity, but in the world of cheminformatics, there is a magical metric that perfectly answers similarity with an objective score ranging from `0` to `1`. That is the "Tanimoto coefficient." In drug discovery, a score of `0.85` or higher is considered to indicate "very high similarity," and it is widely used as an important criterion for virtual screening to quickly narrow down promising candidates from vast compound libraries. In this script, we will work through a practical workflow that quantifies molecular similarity using fingerprints and automatically ranks a database.
%[text] **Learning Objectives**
%[text] - Understand how the Tanimoto coefficient and Dice coefficient work
%[text] - Calculate pairwise similarity using `emk.similarity.tanimoto` / `.dice`
%[text] - Construct an N×N similarity matrix using `emk.similarity.matrix`
%[text] - Rank the database by similarity against a query molecule \
%[text] **Prerequisites**
%[text] - RDKit installed (run `emk.setup.install()` once)
%[text] - F01–F03
%[text] - No additional Toolbox required (works with MATLAB only) \
%[text] Estimated time: 10–15 minutes | How to run: Execute sections one by one with Ctrl+Enter
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
%[text] Initialize the path and Python environment.
%[text] **Always run this section first.**
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:36ed2df2]
%[text] Warm up Python/RDKit process
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
logInfo("F04: Setup complete"); %[output:2c533039]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Tanimoto Similarity
%[text] ### **The "Tanimoto coefficient" measures the ratio of commonalities to the whole**
%[text] In the previous F03, we learned that a molecular fingerprint is a "Yes/No checklist (bit string) representing structural features." The Tanimoto coefficient is a metric that calculates "how many of the items that are checked (ON) in either checklist are also checked in both" when comparing these two checklists. Mathematically, it seeks the ratio of the intersection (A and B) to the union (A or B), where a perfect match yields `1.0` (100%) and no commonalities yield `0.0`.
%[text] This is like comparing movie tastes with a friend. It calculates what fraction of all movies seen by at least one of them were seen by both. Even if it's difficult to compare the shapes of molecules directly, a computer can process the "degree of overlap" of this checklist instantly using bitwise operations, which it excels at. In drug discovery research, **Tanimoto \>= 0.85 is widely used as a benchmark for "high similarity."**
%[text] *Reference: Willett et al., J. Chem. Inf. Comput. Sci. 1998, 38, 983–996.*
mol_ethanol  = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CCO");           % Ethanol
mol_propanol = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CCCO");          % 1-Propanol (similar)
mol_aspirin  = emk.mol.fromSmiles("CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O");  % Aspirin (different)

fp_eth  = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol_ethanol);
fp_prop = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol_propanol);
fp_asp  = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol_aspirin);

t_eth_prop = emk.similarity.tanimoto(fp_eth, fp_prop);
t_eth_asp  = emk.similarity.tanimoto(fp_eth, fp_asp);
t_self     = emk.similarity.tanimoto(fp_eth, fp_eth);  % Always 1.0

logInfo("Tanimoto: Ethanol vs Propanol = %.4f  (similar alcohol)", t_eth_prop); %[output:67cd8eec]
logInfo("Tanimoto: Ethanol vs Aspirin  = %.4f  (quite different)", t_eth_asp); %[output:2161c319]
logInfo("Tanimoto: Ethanol vs Ethanol  = %.4f  (identical)", t_self); %[output:999b5df8]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Dice Similarity
%[text] ### **The "Dice coefficient" weighs commonalities twice**
%[text] Another commonly used metric alongside the Tanimoto coefficient is the "Dice coefficient." The Dice coefficient also measures the overlap of fingerprints, but it has the characteristic of "doubling the value of the common part (intersection) in its evaluation." By using the total number of checks (ON) for each molecule instead of the union of all features (A + B − A∩B) in the denominator, scores tend to be generally higher compared to the Tanimoto coefficient.
%[text] When comparing binary bit vectors, mathematically, the relationship "Dice ≧ Tanimoto" always holds. It's not about which is better or worse; rather, it is used according to the purpose and conventions of the field: "use Tanimoto when you want strict evaluation against the overall denominator," and "use Dice when you want to emphasize how densely common features are included" (the Tanimoto coefficient is most common in drug discovery screening).
%[text] For binary vectors, **Dice \>= Tanimoto** always holds. In practice, both metrics generate nearly the same rankings.
d_eth_prop = emk.similarity.dice(fp_eth, fp_prop);
d_eth_asp  = emk.similarity.dice(fp_eth, fp_asp);

logInfo("Dice: Ethanol vs Propanol = %.4f", d_eth_prop); %[output:4f702f8f]
logInfo("Dice: Ethanol vs Aspirin  = %.4f", d_eth_asp); %[output:68258001]
logInfo("Note: Dice >= Tanimoto always holds: %d and %d", ... %[output:group:12f81556] %[output:19615c52]
    d_eth_prop >= t_eth_prop, d_eth_asp >= t_eth_asp); %[output:group:12f81556] %[output:19615c52]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 1 — Let's test with another alcohol**
%[text] Let's calculate the Tanimoto similarity by comparing methanol (`"CO"`) with ethanol.
%[text] Is it higher or lower than Ethanol vs 1-Propanol? Think about why that is.
%[text] Hint: Methanol has fewer carbon atoms, resulting in fewer "extended environments" shared by the Morgan fingerprint.
% ... (Let's write code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Similarity Matrix of Molecular Set
%[text] ### **Building a Pairwise Similarity Matrix**
%[text] Now, let's use EasyMolKit to build a pairwise similarity matrix for a set of six molecules: three alcohols (Ethanol, 1-Propanol, Isopropanol) and three drugs (Aspirin, Caffeine, Acetaminophen). The procedure is very simple: just pass the fingerprints generated from each molecule (which can remain as Python objects) directly to the functions `emk.similarity.tanimoto` or `emk.similarity.dice`. The `emk.similarity.matrix` calculates the N×N pairwise similarity matrix. The matrix is symmetric, and all diagonal elements are 1.
smiles = ["CCO",                              % Ethanol
          "CCCO",                             % 1-Propanol
          "CC(C)O",                           % 2-Propanol (Isopropanol)
          "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O",           % Aspirin
          "CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C",   % Caffeine
          "CC(=O)NC1=CC=C(C=C1)O"];          % Acetaminophen
names  = ["Ethanol","1-Propanol","Isopropanol","Aspirin","Caffeine","Acetaminophen"];

mols = cellfun(@(s) emk.mol.fromSmiles(s), cellstr(smiles), "UniformOutput", false);
fps  = cellfun(@(m) emk.fingerprint.morgan(m), mols, "UniformOutput", false);

S = emk.similarity.matrix(fps);logInfo("Similarity matrix size: %s", mat2str(size(S))); %[output:4a3732d8]
logInfo("Minimum value outside the diagonal: %.4f", min(S(S < 1))); %[output:00dcac93]
logInfo("Maximum value outside the diagonal: %.4f", max(S(S < 1))); %[output:292c82ff]
%[text] 
%[text] Display the entire matrix
disp("Tanimoto similarity matrix:"); %[output:5e82ca72]
disp(array2table(S, "VariableNames", cellstr(names), "RowNames", cellstr(names))); %[output:4d53efc3]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Visualizing the similarity matrix
%[text] ### **Mapping relationships of multiple molecules**
%[text] When the number of molecules to compare increases beyond a handful, calculating each pair individually is inefficient. By using `emk.similarity.matrix`, you can **calculate all combinations in a pairwise manner** for multiple fingerprints provided and return it as an "N×N square matrix" in MATLAB.
%[text] The diagonal elements of this matrix (the diagonal line from the top left to the bottom right) will always be `1.0` because they represent comparisons with themselves (e.g., Aspirin vs Aspirin). Also, since "the similarity of A and B" is the same as "the similarity of B and A", it results in a symmetric matrix across the diagonal line. By creating this exhaustive matrix, you can visualize "what communities of similar compounds exist" within a group of compounds and obtain a "map of chemical space" for clustering.
%[text] Using a heatmap of the similarity matrix allows you to quickly identify clusters of similar molecules.
figure("Name", "Similarity Matrix", "Position", [100 100 550 450]); %[output:192c6e9c]
imagesc(S); %[output:192c6e9c]
colormap("parula"); %[output:192c6e9c]
colorbar; %[output:192c6e9c]
clim([0 1]); %[output:192c6e9c]
axis square; %[output:192c6e9c]
xticks(1:numel(names));  xticklabels(names);  xtickangle(30); %[output:192c6e9c]
yticks(1:numel(names));  yticklabels(names); %[output:192c6e9c]
title("Pairwise Tanimoto Similarity (Morgan ECFP4)"); %[output:192c6e9c]
%[text] 
%[text] Add numerical annotations to the cells
for r = 1:numel(names) %[output:group:8f278711]
    for c = 1:numel(names)
        text(c, r, sprintf("%.2f", S(r,c)), ... %[output:192c6e9c]
            "HorizontalAlignment", "center", "FontSize", 8, ... %[output:192c6e9c]
            "Color", "white"); %[output:192c6e9c]
    end
end %[output:group:8f278711]
logInfo("Displayed the similarity heatmap."); %[output:7f2e0caf]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 2 — Let's compare using the Dice coefficient**
%[text] Change `Metric` to `"dice"` and recalculate the similarity matrix.
%[text]  `S_dice = emk.similarity.matrix(fps, Metric="dice");`
%[text] Are all the Dice values greater than or equal to the Tanimoto values?
%[text] Does the ranking of the most similar pair and the most dissimilar pair change?
% ... (Let's write code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Ranking by similarity
%[text] ### **Instantly find the "Top N similar" from a vast list**
%[text] The most powerful application of similarity calculations is in database searches. By specifying one "reference molecule (query)" at hand, you can pull the top compounds (Top N) from a "database (library)" containing thousands of compounds, sorted by Tanimoto coefficient in descending order, using a single function called `emk.similarity.rankBy` in EasyMolKit.
%[text] This is the most basic form of "virtual screening" performed in actual pharmaceutical companies to find "hit compounds" from millions of drug candidates. While it would take humans days to visually search through structural formulas, computers can compare fingerprint bit strings at high speed in the background, completing a "ranking of similar compounds" in just milliseconds.
%[text] `emk.similarity.rankBy` returns the molecules most similar to the query at the top. This is the central operation of virtual screening. We will use Caffeine as the query.
query_smiles = "CN1C=NC2=C1C(=O)N(C(=O)N2C)C";   % Caffeine
query_mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(query_smiles);
query_fp  = emk.fingerprint.morgan(query_mol);
%[text] 
%[text] Load everyday chemicals as the database
data     = readtable("data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv", TextType="string");
db_mols  = cellfun(@(s) emk.mol.fromSmiles(s), cellstr(data.SMILES), ...
    "UniformOutput", false);
db_fps   = cellfun(@(m) emk.fingerprint.morgan(m), db_mols, "UniformOutput", false);
%[text] 
%[text] Rank by Tanimoto similarity and return the top 5
result = emk.similarity.rankBy(query_fp, db_fps, 5);

logInfo("Top 5 most similar to Caffeine:"); %[output:3a86ec61]
for k = 1:numel(result.Indices) %[output:group:68d4894f]
    idx = result.Indices(k);
    label = data.CommonName(idx);
    if strlength(label) == 0, label = "(unknown)"; end
    logInfo("  %d. %-20s  Tanimoto=%.4f", k, label, result.Scores(k)); %[output:6fb9735c]
end %[output:group:68d4894f]
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Dice vs Tanimoto — Ranking Comparison
%[text] In most cases, Tanimoto and Dice return the same top hits, but there can be slight differences. Using the same metrics as in papers and prior studies increases the reproducibility of results.
result_dice = emk.similarity.rankBy(query_fp, db_fps, 5, Metric="dice");

logInfo("Top 5 by Dice (Caffeine query):"); %[output:94fe9fc4]
for k = 1:numel(result_dice.Indices) %[output:group:394f0b6a]
    idx = result_dice.Indices(k);
    label = data.CommonName(idx);
    if strlength(label) == 0, label = "(unknown)"; end
    logInfo("  %d. %-20s  Dice=%.4f", k, label, result_dice.Scores(k)); %[output:7a980b5c]
end %[output:group:394f0b6a]
%[text] 
%[text] **✏️ Try It 3 — Let's search with your own query**
