%[text] ## Section 7: Summary
%[text] A summary of the key functions related to molecular similarity learned in this tutorial and important guidelines for practical use.
%[text:table]
%[text] | Function | Description |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | `emk.similarity.tanimoto(fp1, fp2)` | Tanimoto coefficient (0-1) |
%[text] | `emk.similarity.dice(fp1, fp2)` | Dice coefficient (0-1) |
%[text] | `emk.similarity.matrix(fps)` | N×N pairwise matrix (Tanimoto) |
%[text] | `emk.similarity.matrix(fps, Metric="dice")` | N×N pairwise matrix (Dice) |
%[text] | `emk.similarity.rankBy(query, db, N)` | Top N ranking |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] - Tanimoto \>= 0.85 is widely used as a benchmark for "high similarity" in drug discovery.
%[text] - For binary bit vectors, **Dice \>= Tanimoto** always holds true. \
%[text] 
%[text] In the next tutorial, **F05**, we will learn how to search for molecules containing specific functional groups or ring structures using SMARTS-based substructure search.
%%
